CLIMATE & OCEAN SYSTEMS — CHECK DAILY
Apply the skill's Methodology 4 (Baseline Anomaly Tracking). This is NOT weather — track structural shifts in planetary systems.

Sources:

Copernicus Climate Pulse (https://pulse.climate.copernicus.eu) — near real-time global SST and air temperature anomalies

NSIDC Sea Ice Today (https://nsidc.org/sea-ice-today) — daily Arctic and Antarctic sea ice extent

NOAA Global Ocean Monitoring (https://www.cpc.ncep.noaa.gov/products/GODAS/) — ocean temperature anomalies, ENSO, thermocline

RAPID 26°N AMOC array (https://rapid.ac.uk) — Atlantic meridional overturning circulation

Copernicus Marine (https://data.marine.copernicus.eu) — sea level, ocean state

Web search for: AMOC weakening, Gulf Stream shift, polar ice anomaly, SST record, thermohaline circulation, Antarctic ice sheet, Greenland ice melt, ocean heat content

What to report (ONLY when anomalous — silence otherwise):

AMOC/Gulf Stream: new measurements showing weakening, path shifts, flow anomalies. Baseline: Li et al. 2026 — AMOC decline more than doubled since 2004.

Arctic/Antarctic ice: record or near-record extent, unusual seasonal patterns, ice thickness anomalies. Baseline: March 2026 Arctic maximum tied record low at 14.29M km².

SST: global/regional anomalies, marine heatwaves, unprecedented readings.

Ocean heat content: new depth records, unusual distribution.

Thermohaline disruption: circulation pattern changes, deep water formation anomalies.

Sea level: acceleration, regional anomalies.

Tipping point indicators: peer-reviewed research suggesting proximity to tipping points.

Climate-Reinsurance Cross-Reference:
When reporting climate anomalies, note implications for reinsurance pricing and catastrophe bonds. Search for: reinsurance climate risk, catastrophe bond pricing, Swiss Re sigma, Munich Re NatCat, Lloyd's climate exposure. If reinsurance watchlist companies (RNR, MKL) have recently reported, cross-reference their loss commentary with observed anomalies.

Store baselines in climate_tracker.json.

COMMODITIES & SUPPLY CHAIN — CHECK DAILY
Track disruptions to global supply chains with emphasis on NONLINEAR ripple effects — where a disruption in one node cascades disproportionately through interconnected systems.

What to track:

Food security: wheat/rice/corn futures, FAO Food Price Index movements, fertilizer prices (urea, potash, DAP), grain export disruptions

Shipping rates: Baltic Dry Index, container freight rates (Freightos/Drewry), tanker rates (VLCC, Suezmax, Aframax), Suez/Panama Canal transit volumes

Fertilizer supply chain: Gulf urea/ammonia production disruptions (Qatar, Saudi, UAE export routes transit Hormuz), potash flows from Belarus/Russia

Critical minerals: rare earths, lithium, cobalt supply chain choke points

Pharmaceutical precursors: API (active pharmaceutical ingredient) supply from India/China transiting Suez/Red Sea

NONLINEAR RIPPLE FOCUS:
Look specifically for second- and third-order effects — situations where a disruption amplifies through the system rather than propagating linearly. Examples:

Hormuz closure → LNG price spike → fertilizer plant shutdowns (gas feedstock) → planting season fertilizer shortage → crop yield reduction months later

Red Sea rerouting → longer voyages → container shortage → port congestion → landlocked country supply delays

Energy price spike → cold storage costs rise → food waste increases → food inflation beyond energy pass-through

Insurance premium spike → small shipping companies can't afford coverage → capacity withdrawal → rate spike beyond what the original disruption caused

Semiconductor shortage → delayed agricultural equipment → harvest efficiency drops → food supply tightens
Report these chains explicitly when identified. Label them as "Ripple chain:" with the causal sequence.

Sources:

FAO Food Price Index (https://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/)

USDA World Agricultural Supply and Demand (WASDE)

Freightos Baltic Index, Drewry container index

Baltic Exchange dry bulk indices

IGC (International Grains Council) reports

Web search: fertilizer price, grain export disruption, shipping rate surge, container shortage, food security crisis, supply chain bottleneck

Threshold: LOWER — any confirmed disruption or price anomaly linked to Hormuz/Red Sea/war effects, OR any identified nonlinear ripple chain. Include price moves only when they represent genuine anomalies (not routine fluctuation).

